 Indian -- t17. Euphemism in the Forest -- t18. What’s the Difference Between a Peace Corps Worker and an Anthropologist? -- t19. Traditional Resource Use and Ethnoeconomics -- t20. Enhancing Social Capital -- tAppendix: Findings and Recommendations -- tContributors -- tIndex -- tBackmatter0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aFrom the pre-Columbian era to the present, native Amazonians have shaped the land around them, emphasizing utilization, conservation, and sustainability. These priorities stand in stark contrast to colonial and contemporary exploitation of Amazonia by outside interests. With essays from environmental scientists, botanists, and anthropologists, this volume explores the various effects of human development on Amazonia. The contributors argue that by protecting and drawing on local knowledge and values, further environmental ruin can be avoided.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 7aSCIENCE / Life Sciences / Ecology.2bisacsh1 aAllen, Elizabeth, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBalick, Michael J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBalick, Michael, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBarrow, Christopher, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBridgewater, Samuel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCavalcanti, Clóvis, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aClement, Charles R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFearnside, Philip M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFurley, Peter A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHall, Anthony, econtributor.